          "questionText": "What is being used up to push current through the resistance of the circuit conductors?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Energy",
            "Electrical pressure",
            "Voltage"
          ],
          "hint": "Think about what is lost to overcome 'electrical friction'.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why does voltage drop occur in every functional circuit, even if there are no faults or loose connections?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "All conductors have some inherent resistance",
        "Current flowing through resistance always results in energy loss",
        "Energy is required to overcome the resistance of the cables",
        "It is a natural result of current passing through a conductor"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP2"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider the relationship between current flow and the resistance found in all real-world materials."
    },
    {
      "title": "Circuit Implications (AC4.3)",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "Why is copper preferred over materials with higher resistivity for general electrical wiring?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Low resistivity",
            "Lower resistance"
          ],
          "hint": "Lower resistivity allows for better efficiency without needing massive cables.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "If the resistance of a cable is increased, what happens to the resulting voltage drop?",
