          "hint": "More opposition makes it harder for the pressure to stay the same.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP3"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the practical goal of an electrician when selecting cable sizes regarding voltage levels?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Keep voltage drop within limits",
            "Minimize voltage drop",
            "Ensure safe limits"
          ],
          "hint": "Regulations define how much 'loss' is acceptable.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP4"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does the resistivity of a chosen conductor material directly impact the overall efficiency of an electrical installation?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Resistivity determines the base resistance of the circuit",
        "Lower resistivity reduces the energy lost as heat or voltage drop",
        "Material choice dictates how much voltage reaches the load",
        "High resistivity materials would require much larger cables to maintain efficiency"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP2",
        "TP3"
      ],
      "hint": "Connect the material's 'DNA' to the amount of energy lost during operation."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice",
    "objective": "Identify the correct technical term for electrical pressure loss in a specific circuit scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Scenario: An electrician installs a 40-metre run of 4.0mm² copper cable to a workshop socket.",
      "1. The copper material itself has an inherent property that opposes current flow, regardless of the cable's size.",
      "2. Because the cable is 40 metres long, it has a specific total amount of opposition measured in Ohms.",
      "3. When a heavy power tool is used, the electrical pressure at the workshop socket is 6V lower than at the main board."
    ],
    "questionText": "Based on the scenario above, what is the correct technical term for the 6V loss described in step 3?",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Voltage Drop"
    ],
    "hint": "Think about the 'drop' in electrical pressure that occurs when current overcomes resistance."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Practice",
    "objective": "Explain the relationship between material properties and circuit outcomes.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Consider two identical 10-metre cables: one is made of copper and the other is made of aluminum.",
      "Aluminum has a higher resistivity than copper.",
      "When these cables are used in a circuit, the aluminum cable will always show a higher total resistance than the copper cable of the same size."
    ],
    "questionText": "Explain how the higher resistivity of the aluminum material results in a larger voltage drop at the end of the cable run.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The higher resistivity of the aluminum increases the total resistance of the cable, which causes more electrical pressure to be lost as voltage drop when current flows."
    ],
    "hint": "Link the material property (resistivity) to the conductor's opposition (resistance) and then to the resulting loss of pressure."
  }
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Material Choice and Circuit Performance",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between a material's resistivity, the resulting resistance of the conductor, and the inevitable voltage drop produced in a functional circuit.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Resistivity is the inherent property of the material (the 'electrical DNA').",
      "Resistance is the total opposition of the specific cable run.",
      "Voltage drop is the loss of electrical pressure across that resistance."
    ],
    "questionText": "An electrician is considering replacing a standard copper cable with a cheaper alloy cable that has a significantly higher resistivity. Explain why using this higher-resistivity material for the same length and thickness of wire would result in a lower voltage being measured at the end of the circuit when the load is switched on.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Higher resistivity means the material itself has a greater inherent opposition to current flow.",
      "This higher resistivity directly increases the total resistance (measured in Ohms) of that specific cable run.",
      "When current flows through this increased resistance, more electrical pressure is 'used up' or lost as voltage drop, leaving less voltage available at the end of the circuit."
    ],
    "hint": "Connect the material's 'DNA' (resistivity) to the total 'friction' (resistance) and then to the 'pressure loss' (voltage drop)."
  }
}

